Appendix 4    39 
A.   Selection Criteria 

To help identify appropriate roads for future projects, a set of selection criteria has been 
proposed. A candidate road should: 

(i)  be an existing or former road (i.e., a road bench exists and restitution of a 
trafficable road will not require major earthwork or construction of structures); 

(ii)  connect a populous (>5,000 people) and/or potentially economically significant 
area(s) to the existing highway network; 

(iii)  have actual or expected traffic that exceeds an annual average of 200 vehicles 
per day; 

(iv)  meet the 12% economic internal rate of return for the proposed investment in 
road improvement; 

(v)  not duplicate a road that is already part of the Investment Program (if some 
diversion of existing traffic is expected, the impact on the viability of the existing 
route must be taken into account in the analysis); 

(vi)  have  the  support  of  the  local  population  and  the  district  and  provincial 
administrations; 

(vii)  not require removal of permanent structures; 

(viii)  be on government land, or there should be an agreement with the affected 
community that allows (a) use of land for road improvement works initially, and 
(b)  acquisition  of  land  after  going  through  the  necessary  procedures  and 
payment of required compensation;  

(ix)  not endanger or provide access to at-risk fauna or flora; and 

(x)  not have any other significant adverse environmental or social impacts.
